Yeah, I have a master’s in literature (I know, I know. I wanted to teach it, but fuck that.) and originality is just an illusion. I think for the most part, stories all follow some template whether they intend to or not. It’s where you differ from those templates or the new innovations to the old formula that makes good “new” stories.

My hot take is that it’s not like back in the day with the forerunners like Mary Shelley’s Frankenstein or Margaret Cavendish's The Description of a New World, Called the Blazing-World or going a bit further like Isaac Asimov, H.G Wells bangers. The paths have been so heavily tread in my opinion to get innovation you need to go the opposite direction.

Now to the real hot take, take isekai anime for an example. It is so overwhelmingly over saturated that rather than trying to make something unique and revolutionary, they must fight to find the key that can set them apart. From that reiteration and recursive storytelling, you sometimes get a polished gem like Ascendance of a Bookworm. I have a soft spot for some trashy media, so maybe I’m biased. And I’m not going to say it’s revolutionary literature, but my whole point is that the way to a new path is through recursion and reiterative exploration of what we have already tread.

Now, back to sci-fi. A great example of this is The Illuminae Files Series by Amie Kaufman, which takes the already-over saturated sci-fi concept of the out of control AI core story, and really takes it new places, I would highly recommend it, especially in audiobook form. The entire story is told through an investigation and mostly through log files, communications between characters, etc.

>>60708040
The term is pulp. But both types have always existed, and lots of other types besides. There's plenty of science fiction that doesn't delve into detail with its technology (or other elements), and there's plenty of pulp that wastes pages on useless telling instead of showing. One old book I tried to read had a terrible writing style and introduced its main character by listing his Phd's. This was pulp about invisible sky pirates (and yes, it went into detailed mumbo jumbo explaining the fictional invisibility). It's a contemporary of Brave New World, which is widely regarded as literature, and which doesn't go into technical detail.

The one caveat I would admit to is that pulp has fallen out of fashion these days, and doesn't get the time of day. But the people hostile to pulp are nearly as hostile to detailed, nitty-gritty type science fiction. That's the impression I get from reading Clarkesworld, at least. Though I suppose there are still stories that resonate certain pulp values. What's new, however, and my own personal extreme dislike, are the slummers. People who are clearly attempting to write literary fiction but shoehorn in some science fiction or fantasy conceit. Maybe they truly think they're writing science fiction, maybe they're fully aware they're cynically trying to access a less prestigious market, but I loathe them.

Not him, but Stranger in a Strange Land is one of Heinlein's better known novels. Paradoxically it is not one of his stronger works. It's not the raging dumpster fire that Time Enough for Love is, but it's pretty bad. I don't know how it fits into HFY, though. It's mainly about a human infant raised by Martians, who comes back to Earth and is basically Space Jesus, here to tell all you squares that your aversion to cannibalism is totally irrational and uncool.

I know a Heinlein had a lot of vociferous fans but his short stories and his 1950s "juveniles" were far and away his best work. And the massive stroke he had in 1970 caused him permanent brain damage right around the time that he had become popular enough to be able to shop his novels around to various publishing houses and tell the editors "no, you aren't changing that." The eighteen years between then and his death were punctuated with novels exploring his obsession with incest, including one in which a time-traveler goes back in time to seduce his own mother, with lots and lots of lovingly detailed explicit sex.

Of course the sci-fi fandom itself was a nest of creeps, weirdos, and pederasts long before the Internet. Look up Walter Breen and Marion Zimmer Bradley some time. Lots of the old pulp writers were creeps, weirdos, and crazies, too. The Venn diagram of "pulp detective writers" and "pulp sci-fi writers" shows considerable overlap, because of these guys wrote detective stories and Westerns under two dozen names when skiffy wasn't paying the bills.

Actually all of this makes me feel the need for a unicorn chaser.
